1
00:00:05,700 --> 00:00:09,750
Clanker City! The big smoke! The city of ten thousand gears!

2
00:00:09,750 --> 00:00:14,480
One small maintenance-bot, one dream, and not so much as an oil can to my name.

3
00:00:14,700 --> 00:00:19,200
Thanks for the ride! I'll catch the return ferry once I'm rich and famous.

4
00:00:20,530 --> 00:00:23,010
...

5
00:00:23,010 --> 00:00:25,480
That clunk sounded expensive.

6
00:00:26,140 --> 00:00:28,630
That clunk sounded PERMANENT.

7
00:00:28,630 --> 00:00:35,620
Well. Guess I live here now.

8
00:00:35,620 --> 00:00:39,650
The neon sign dips. The tavern window. The lit windows across the water. All together, like the city skipped a heartbeat.

9
00:00:44,510 --> 00:00:47,350
WELCOME TO CLANKER CITY. POP. 8,01,1.

10
00:00:47,350 --> 00:00:51,490
Population eight-oh-one-comma-one. The punctuation died first.

11
00:00:51,490 --> 00:00:56,720
Something inside it rattles on every flicker. Loose hardware. Practically an invoice.

12
00:01:01,100 --> 00:01:04,360
Maybe a good honest whack will fix the display.

13
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:08,509
It rained a bolt. In this town that's basically a tip.

14
00:01:13,320 --> 00:01:18,320
One bolt. Only eight thousand and ten more and I can afford a personality upgrade.

15
00:01:24,020 --> 00:01:27,080
Official city notice, hot off the press:

16
00:01:27,080 --> 00:01:31,660
'DYNAMO MAINTENANCE: NOTHING IS WRONG. NOTHING HAS EVER BEEN WRONG.'

17
00:01:31,660 --> 00:01:34,919
'DO NOT STOCKPILE OIL. SIGNED, MAYOR PISTON.'

18
00:01:34,919 --> 00:01:39,720
The Great Dynamo powers every bot on this island. Including me, as of today.

19
00:01:39,720 --> 00:01:47,530
Not wires — the hum. It keeps every mainspring on the island wound. Remotely. Steam bot, clockwork bot, engine bot: all spring-banked.

20
00:01:47,530 --> 00:01:51,690
Hand-winding is the backup. Crude, short-burst, off-warranty.

21
00:01:51,690 --> 00:01:55,380
So that notice is the scariest thing I've ever read.

22
00:01:59,539 --> 00:02:02,580
Let me read it first. I'm a maintenance-bot, not a barbarian.

23
00:02:09,350 --> 00:02:11,950
Hello up there! Lovely evening!

24
00:02:13,040 --> 00:02:17,370
...

25
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:47,760
A player piano, playing itself. It's missing three keys.

26
00:02:47,760 --> 00:02:50,810
...That feels thematically significant.

27
00:02:57,560 --> 00:03:01,480
Hold still, sir. This is a certified maintenance procedure.

28
00:03:02,150 --> 00:03:07,570
The bolt slots into the ratchet. The servo unwinds. The glass, at long last, comes down.

29
00:03:07,570 --> 00:03:10,829
My fortune. Reduced to eight thousand and nine.

30
00:03:11,049 --> 00:03:16,049
He flips me a drink token. Says Flange takes those as table stakes at the dartboard.

31
00:03:22,820 --> 00:03:27,600
I lean in casually. Extremely casually. Nobody has ever leaned this casually.

32
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:32,579
The one in the hat says: you CLANG twice, then once, then twice, you barnacle.

33
00:03:32,579 --> 00:03:35,620
I am definitely not supposed to know that.

34
00:03:42,250 --> 00:03:44,420
Token on the rail. Game on.

35
00:03:45,079 --> 00:03:47,030
Dart one: the wall.

36
00:03:47,690 --> 00:03:50,090
Dart two: a different wall.

37
00:03:50,530 --> 00:03:54,450
Dart three is in the ocean. We're indoors. Nobody knows.

38
00:03:54,450 --> 00:04:00,320
Flange is laughing so hard he goes for the showboat finish: three darts, one throw, behind the back.

39
00:04:01,220 --> 00:04:05,760
His shoulder servo overheats with a noise like bacon achieving liftoff.

40
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:10,549
House rules: the overheated party forfeits the wager. The oil can is mine.

41
00:04:10,549 --> 00:04:14,660
Losing this badly took real skill. Nobody will ever believe that.

42
00:04:32,100 --> 00:04:34,710
Open wide, Betty. Doctor's orders.

43
00:04:35,600 --> 00:04:38,860
The oil goes in. Twenty years of squeak go out.

44
00:04:38,860 --> 00:04:43,230
Betty sets the crate down with the gentleness of a very large aunt.

45
00:04:48,910 --> 00:04:51,960
It's eight feet up. Fine: four. My arms are stock parts and the principle is load-bearing.

46
00:04:51,960 --> 00:04:57,830
Betty could set it down, if anyone gave her a drink of oil.

47
00:04:57,830 --> 00:05:02,160
The lid argues. I argue back with a plank.

48
00:05:29,370 --> 00:05:36,130
Rivet's the name, he says. Knows everything, sells most of it. Today only: the welcome bundle, three facts, free.

49
00:05:36,130 --> 00:05:41,780
The funicular to Midtown takes ten bolts. Exact change. Gates can count — it's all they do.

50
00:05:41,780 --> 00:05:47,860
Fact two, on the house, because I look like rain: the Dynamo is winding down, whatever the posters say.

51
00:05:48,070 --> 00:05:54,600
The Order that built it left three wind-up keys behind. All three together could wind the city back up. Or down.

52
00:05:54,600 --> 00:06:00,480
Fact three: the harbor keeps everything this town drops, and that dumpster is — legally — his.

53
00:06:06,810 --> 00:06:11,380
Someone sprayed DYNAMO IS FINE. Crossed out. Under it, smaller: IT IS NOT.

54
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:14,220
Under that, very small: NO REFUNDS.

55
00:06:19,070 --> 00:06:20,820
Knock knock.

56
00:06:20,820 --> 00:06:26,640
The slot opens. The same eye as the tavern. 'This is the BACK back door. STILL Act Three, buddy.'

57
00:06:26,640 --> 00:06:30,220
This organization has remarkable message discipline.

58
00:06:35,280 --> 00:06:41,230
Inside: one rubber duck, seized. One manual in a language of pure grease. And a magnet on a string.

59
00:06:41,230 --> 00:06:46,340
In a town held together by bolts, a magnet on a string is a license to print money.

60
00:06:58,150 --> 00:07:01,900
Down goes the magnet, on the city's last honest string.

61
00:07:02,580 --> 00:07:05,420
Something bites. Several somethings.

62
00:07:05,420 --> 00:07:09,370
Nine bolts. This city has been tipping the ocean for years.

63
00:07:25,350 --> 00:07:29,560
I feed it the fistful. It counts, blinks NINE, and returns the lot.

64
00:07:29,780 --> 00:07:33,310
Smug, for a gate. Rivet would know where a tenth grows.

65
00:07:38,830 --> 00:07:43,650
Rivet's the name, he says. Knows everything, sells most of it. Today only: the welcome bundle, three facts, free.

66
00:07:43,870 --> 00:07:50,680
The funicular to Midtown takes ten bolts. Exact change. Gates can count — it's all they do.

67
00:07:50,680 --> 00:07:56,820
Fact two, on the house, because I look like rain: the Dynamo is winding down, whatever the posters say.

68
00:07:56,820 --> 00:08:00,290
The Order that built it left three wind-up keys behind. All three together could wind the city back up. Or down.

69
00:08:00,290 --> 00:08:05,170
Fact three: the harbor keeps everything this town drops, and that dumpster is — legally — his.

70
00:08:05,170 --> 00:08:07,860
Nine bolts, I tell him. He appraises my pockets from four feet away. Correctly.

71
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:18,300
Ten bolts in the hopper. It counts them twice. Trust died in this town years ago.

72
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:24,350
The gate ratchets up, and a little brass car rolls down to meet me, lit up like a promise.

73
00:08:24,350 --> 00:08:27,220
Uptown. I can hear the neon from here.

74
00:08:31,430 --> 00:08:36,300
Gate's open, car's lit. Midtown keeps glittering like it doesn't know I'm coming.

75
00:08:36,300 --> 00:08:39,909
Midtown can wait. The Dynamo, I'm less sure about.

76
00:08:45,970 --> 00:08:52,260
Ten bolts in the hopper. It counts them twice. Trust died in this town years ago.

77
00:08:52,260 --> 00:08:56,870
The gate ratchets up, and a little brass car rolls down to meet me, lit up like a promise.

78
00:08:56,870 --> 00:09:01,760
Uptown. I can hear the neon from here.

79
00:09:01,980 --> 00:09:04,160
The fare box wants ten bolts. I have pockets, and ambition.

80
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:15,490
Talent night, tonight, he says. Grand prize: an oil voucher and a backstage pass.

81
00:09:15,490 --> 00:09:21,290
Backstage. Where Madame Voltina reads fortunes. And guards... things. He doesn't say what things.

82
00:09:21,290 --> 00:09:26,640
Sign-up needs a stage name and an act. I have a name, and a key the size of my forearm.

83
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:29,790
He says, quote, that's more act than most.

84
00:09:30,010 --> 00:09:35,780
You keep your props, he adds, before I can ask. House insurance won't survive a second Houdini.

85
00:09:41,520 --> 00:09:45,550
The Great Dynamo, up the hill, behind a fence with opinions.

86
00:09:45,550 --> 00:09:50,960
Every bot on this island runs on that hum. Including me. The hum is flat by half a step.

87
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:54,780
Half a step doesn't sound like much. Neither did the clunk.

88
00:09:59,430 --> 00:10:03,460
City Hall. The banner says NOTHING IS WRONG. It's brand new.

89
00:10:03,460 --> 00:10:07,980
They replaced the old banner. The old one said the same thing, smaller.

90
00:10:12,010 --> 00:10:16,790
An aide opens the door exactly nine degrees. The Mayor is not seeing anyone.

91
00:10:16,790 --> 00:10:19,920
Especially, he adds, anyone holding paper.

92
00:10:25,900 --> 00:10:31,070
I pitch the act: THE AMAZING SPROCKET WINDS HIMSELF UP. With a real key. On stage.

93
00:10:31,070 --> 00:10:35,030
The clerk has seen everything twice, and he still blinks.

94
00:10:35,030 --> 00:10:39,100
My name goes up on the marquee while I'm still holding the pen.

95
00:10:39,100 --> 00:10:41,800
I keep the key. It's the act.

96
00:10:46,480 --> 00:10:49,780
There it is. SPROCKET. On a marquee. In lights.

97
00:10:49,780 --> 00:10:53,380
Two of the bulbs are out. The rest are compensating.

98
00:10:53,600 --> 00:10:57,650
Talent night. Tonight. No pressure. The marquee is the pressure.

99
00:11:03,750 --> 00:11:10,230
The doors open for performers. I'm a spectator with a forearm-sized key. The doors can tell.

100
00:11:30,740 --> 00:11:35,830
Sprocket, he says, reading the marquee off my face. The wind-up act. You're on next.

101
00:11:35,830 --> 00:11:42,370
One problem: the spotlight operator went into low-power mode during the juggler. The juggler had that effect.

102
00:11:42,370 --> 00:11:47,340
House rule: no spot, no act. He says it like the rule has a plaque somewhere.

103
00:11:47,340 --> 00:11:52,980
He looks from my key to the dark booth and back. He likes my chances, he says. Conditionally.

104
00:11:58,940 --> 00:12:02,470
I try some crowd work. How's everybody doing tonight?

105
00:12:02,470 --> 00:12:05,370
A voice from the dark: 'WORSE NOW.'

106
00:12:09,820 --> 00:12:13,160
I rap on the booth. HOUSE LIGHTS, BUDDY. SHOWTIME.

107
00:12:13,380 --> 00:12:18,570
His eye flickers up through three shades of amber. He checks the program, then checks me.

108
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:23,740
He mouths: 'the wind-up act?' I nod. He cracks every knuckle he has. Both of them.

109
00:12:30,960 --> 00:12:36,240
The curtain opens. The house goes quiet the way a dropped wrench goes quiet. Mid-air.

110
00:12:36,240 --> 00:12:40,270
I wind myself. Eight full turns. Regulation maximum is five.

111
00:12:40,490 --> 00:12:42,450
The spring lets go.

112
00:12:42,450 --> 00:12:45,570
I am now performing unscheduled acrobatics.

113
00:12:45,570 --> 00:12:50,030
The proscenium and I meet several times. It gives as good as it gets.

114
00:12:50,030 --> 00:12:55,010
I land in the spotlight. On my feet. Nobody is more surprised than the feet.

115
00:12:55,010 --> 00:12:59,960
Silence. Then the house comes apart. The bots who can't stand wave their wheels.

116
00:12:59,960 --> 00:13:05,160
The emcee declares it the most honest act in Grand Cog history. I don't correct him.

117
00:13:05,160 --> 00:13:10,330
First prize: one oil voucher, and a backstage pass on a lanyard of bicycle chain.

118
00:13:10,330 --> 00:13:16,860
The spring spat the key to the boards at launch. I go to collect it for the bow — my hand closes on applause.

119
00:13:16,860 --> 00:13:22,590
A hook on a line whips up past the proscenium. Fishing tackle. Somebody else's magnet-on-a-string.

120
00:13:22,820 --> 00:13:26,720
Up on the catwalk, a hatch clicks shut. Two clangs. One. Two.

121
00:13:26,720 --> 00:13:33,880
The hats from the card table. The spyglass from the catwalk. I hand-delivered the thing — lit stage, my name in bulbs.

122
00:13:33,880 --> 00:13:37,330
Everyone in this house saw a triumph. I saw a hatch.

123
00:13:42,510 --> 00:13:48,750
I flash the pass. The stagehand reads it twice. Nothing in his build explains how he steps aside, but he does.

124
00:13:48,750 --> 00:13:55,430
The dark behind him smells like ozone and incense. A voice from it says: 'I have been expecting you, key-bearer.'

125
00:13:55,430 --> 00:14:02,600
I start to explain about the key. 'I know,' says the voice. 'Ask me sometime about the key that winds itself. Mind the cables.'

126
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:06,720
Madame Voltina. I'm going to need a minute, and possibly a will.

